# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: texture-compression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] Full details of ASTC were first presented publicly at the High Performance Graphics 2012 conference, in a paper by Olson et al. entitled "Adaptive Scalable Texture Compression".
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] ASTC was adopted as an official extension for both OpenGL and OpenGL ES by the Khronos Group on 6 August 2012.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] On Linux, all Gallium 3D drivers have a software fallback since 2018, so ASTC can be used on any AMD Radeon GPU.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The method of compression is an evolution of Color Cell Compression with features including numerous closely spaced fractional bit rates, multiple color formats, support for high-dynamic-range (HDR) textures, and real 3D texture support.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The stated primary design goal for ASTC is to enable content developers to have better control over the space/quality tradeoff inherent in any lossy compression scheme.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] With ASTC, the ratio between adjacent bit rates is of the order of 25%, making it less expensive to increase quality for a given texture.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] Encoding different assets often requires different color formats.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] ASTC allows a wide choice of input formats, including luminance-only, luminance-alpha, RGB, RGBA, and modes optimized for surface normals.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The designer can thus choose the optimal format without having to support multiple different compression schemes.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The choices of bit rate and color format do not constrain each other, so that it's possible to choose from a large number of combinations.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] Despite this flexibility, ASTC achieves better peak signal-to-noise ratios than PVRTC, S3TC, and ETC2 when measured at 2 and 3.56 bits per texel.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] For HDR textures, it produces results comparable to BC6H at 8 bits per texel.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The algorithm decouples the resolution of the weight grid from the texels, allowing each block to have a grid of up to 64 weights.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] These weights are then interpolated to determine the values for each texel using bilinear or trilinear interpolation.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] In dual-plane mode, two separate weight values are specified for each texel.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] One color channel can be designated as the second plane and interpolated using an independent weight grid, selected via a 2-bit component selector.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] This is particularly useful for uncorrelated channels like alpha.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] Void-extent blocks are also available to efficiently encode constant color areas.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] A fundamental component of ASTC is Bounded Integer Sequence Encoding (BISE), a low-level coding scheme that allows sequences of data values to be represented using a fractional number of bits per value.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] This is used for efficient non-power-of-two quantization of both color endpoints and weights.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] ASTC also supports multi-partitioning, allowing a block to be divided into up to four spatial subsets, each with its own color endpoints.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] For high-dynamic-range (HDR) textures, it uses a pseudo-logarithmic representation to maintain consistent precision across a wide range of values.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] ASTC supports anywhere from 1 to 4 channels.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] In modes with 2–4 channels, one of the channels can be treated as "uncorrelated" and be given a separate gradient for prediction.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] In any case, the data is decoded as RGBA.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] Each of these may be encoded as low or high dynamic range.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The encoder selects color formats independently for each block in the image.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] In practice, ASTC may be used to represent data other than color.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] For example, the L+A format may be used to represent "X+Y", a normal map with uncorrelated components; the "RG+B" format can be used to represent XY+Z.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The `astc-encoder` software supplied by ARM supports "X+Y" generation with the `-normal` option.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The shader is expected to treat the decoded output as a swizzled texture.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] ASTC textures are compressed using a fixed block size of 128 bits, but with a variable block footprint ranging from 4×4 texels up to 12×12 texels.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The available bit rates thus range from 8 bits per texel down to 0.89 bits per texel, with fine steps in between.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] In the above table, the "Increment" column shows the additional storage required to store a texture using this bit rate, as compared to the next smallest.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] Block footprints are presented as width × height.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] ASTC 3D textures are compressed using a fixed block size of 128 bits, as for 2D but with a variable block footprint ranging from 3×3×3 texels up to 6×6×6 texels.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The available bit rates thus range from 4.74 bits per texel down to 0.59 bits per texel, with fine steps in between.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] Block footprints are presented as width × height × depth.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] UASTC (Universal ASTC) is a subset of ASTC specified by Binomial.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] The format is used in their Basis Universal "supercompressed" GPU texture format, which adds extra compression over compressed texture formats such as UASTC and ETC1S and allows for efficient conversion from UASTC/ETC1S to compressed texture formats directly usable by GPUs.
[src:texture-compression/adaptive-scalable-texture-compression] UASTC, as part of Basis Universal, is part of the KTX (Khronos Texture) file format.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] The original 'ETC1' compression scheme provides 6x compression of 24-bit RGB data.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] It does not port the compression of images with Alpha components, although there are work-arounds for this.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] ETC1 takes 4x4 groups of pixel data and compresses each into a single 64-bit word.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] The 4×4 pixel group is first divided into two 4×2 chunks - either horizontally or vertically.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] Each half is given a base color - either using 4/4/4 RGB or by giving one of them a 5/5/5 RGB and having the other be a 3/3/3 bit offset from that base.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] Each 4×2 region also has a 3-bit brightness range selection.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] Each pixel is then offset from the base color by adding one of four signed values to the base color for its half of the 4×4 group.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] This format is a part of the OpenGL ES graphics standard extensions for embedded devices such as mobile phones and has been approved by the Khronos Group for use in the WebGL graphics standard for browser-side World Wide Web graphics.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] Android version 2.2 (Froyo) includes support for ETC1.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] The 'ETC2' scheme expands ETC1 in a backwards-compatible way to provide higher quality RGB compression, as well as compression of RGBA (RGB plus alpha).
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] sRGB variants of the above codecs are also available.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] EAC is built on the same principles as ETC1/ETC2 but is used for one- or two-channel data.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] The RGBA and RG11 formats are encoded in 128 bits per 4x4 block, while the rest are encoded in 64 bits per block.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] For RGBA, the RGB channels are encoded in a regular 64-bit block, while the A channel gets its own 64-bit block.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] RG11 formats are encoded similarly, with one 64-bit block per component.
[src:texture-compression/ericsson-texture-compression] A software utility called **ETCPACK** for compression and decompression of ETC1/ETC2 textures is available for free download in code form from Ericsson on GitHub.
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] These differ from strictly block-based texture formats such as S3TC and Ericsson Texture Compression (ETC) in that the compressed image is represented by two lower resolution images which are bilinearly upscaled and then blended according to low precision, per-pixel weights.
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] They also differ in that they support ARGB data in both 4-bpp and 2-bpp modes.
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] PVRTC is the compressed texture format used in the Nokia N9 and all generations of the iPhone, iPod Touch, and iPad.
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] It is also supported in certain Android devices, that use PowerVR GPUs.
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] In both PVRTC and PVRTC2, texture data is stored in blocks (but note that the decoding of any 2x2 set of texels requires access to 4 of these blocks.) A data block always occupies 64 bits (8 bytes) of storage/memory space and thus, in 4-bit mode (4bpp), there will be one block for each 4×4 pixels.
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] In 2-bit mode (2-bpp), there will be one block for every 8×4 pixels.
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] For example, a 1024×1024 4-bpp PVRTC texture would have 65,536 blocks and take 524,288 bytes of storage/memory space.
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] In some hardware implementations, the blocks are arranged in a variant of Morton order.
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] With PVRTC there are six different variables stored in each block: Modulation data (32 bits), punch-through alpha flag (1 bit), color A (15 bits), color A opaque flag (1 bit), color B (14 bits) and color B opaque flag (1 bit).
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] With PVRTC2 there are six different variables stored to one block: Modulation data (32 bits), modulation flag (1 bit), color B (14 bits), hard transition flag (1 bit), color A (15 bits) and opacity flag (1 bit).
[src:texture-compression/pvrtc] Although in PVRTC the opacity flags can be set independently for the A & B colours, in PVRTC2, Color A and Color B must both be in same format (i.e. either both RGB or both RGBA).
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] US 5956431 A) of the multiple USPTO patents on S3 Texture Compression expired on October 2, 2017.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] At least one continuation patent, US6,775,417, however had a 165-day extension.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] This continuation patent expired on March 16, 2018.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] There are five variations of the S3TC algorithm (named **DXT1** through **DXT5**, referring to the FourCC code assigned by Microsoft to each format), each designed for specific types of image data.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] All convert a 4×4 block of pixels to a 64-bit or 128-bit quantity, resulting in compression ratios of 6:1 with 24-bit RGB input data or 4:1 with 32-bit RGBA input data.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] S3TC is a lossy compression algorithm, resulting in image quality degradation, an effect which is minimized by the ability to increase texture resolutions while maintaining the same memory requirements.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] Hand-drawn cartoon-like images do not compress well, nor do normal map data, both of which usually generate artifacts.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] Like many modern image compression algorithms, S3TC only specifies the method used to decompress images, allowing implementers to design the compression algorithm to suit their specific needs, although the patent still covers compression algorithms.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] The Nvidia GeForce 256 through to GeForce 4 cards also used 16-bit interpolation to render DXT1 textures, which resulted in banding when unpacking textures with color gradients.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] Again, this created an unfavorable impression of texture compression, not related to the fundamentals of the codec itself.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] DXT1 (also known as Block Compression 1 or BC1) is the smallest variation of S3TC, storing 16 input pixels in 64 bits of output, consisting of two 16-bit RGB 5:6:5 color values $c_{0}$ and $c_{1}$ , and a 4×4 two-bit lookup table.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] This mode operates similarly to mode 0xC0 of the original Apple Video codec.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] This color sometimes causes a black border surrounding the transparent area when linear texture filtering and alpha test is used, due to colors being interpolated between the color of opaque texel and neighbouring black transparent texel.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] The lookup table is then consulted to determine the color value for each pixel, with a value of 0 corresponding to $c_{0}$ and a value of 3 corresponding to $c_{3}$ .
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] In DXT2, the color data is interpreted as being premultiplied by alpha, in DXT3 it is interpreted as not having been premultiplied by alpha.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] Typically DXT2/3 are well suited to images with sharp alpha transitions, between translucent and opaque areas.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] DXT4 and DXT5 (collectively also known as Block Compression 3 or BC3) converts 16 input pixels into 128 bits of output, consisting of 64 bits of alpha channel data (two 8-bit alpha values and a 4×4 3-bit lookup table) followed by 64 bits of color data (encoded the same way as DXT1).
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] The lookup table is then consulted to determine the alpha value for each pixel, with a value of 0 corresponding to $\alpha _{0}$ and a value of 7 corresponding to $\alpha _{7}$ .
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] DXT4's color data is premultiplied by alpha, whereas DXT5's is not.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] Because DXT4/5 use an interpolated alpha scheme, they generally produce superior results for alpha (transparency) gradients than DXT2/3.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] BC4 and BC5 (Block Compression 4 and 5) are added in Direct3D 10.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] They reuse the alpha channel encoding found in DXT4/5 (BC3).
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] BC6H (sometimes BC6) and BC7 (Block Compression 6H and 7) are added in Direct3D 11.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] BC6H and BC7 have a much more complex algorithm with a selection of encoding modes.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] These two modes are also specified much more exactly, with ranges of accepted deviation.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] Earlier BCn modes decode slightly differently among GPU vendors.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] BCn textures can be further compressed for on-disk storage and distribution (texture supercompression).
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] An application would decompress this extra layer and send the BCn data to the GPU as usual.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] BCn can be combined with Oodle Texture, a lossy preprocessor that modifies the input texture so that the BCn output is more easily compressed by a LZ77 compressor (rate–distortion optimization).
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] BC7 specifically can also use "bc7prep", a lossless pass to re-encode the texture in a more compressible form (requiring its inverse at decompression).
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] crunch is another tool that performs RDO and optionally further re-encoding.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] In 2021, Microsoft produced a "BCPack" compression algorithm specifically for BCn-compressed textures.
[src:texture-compression/s3-texture-compression] Xbox series X and S have hardware support for decompressing BCPack streams.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Texture compression can be applied to reduce memory usage at runtime.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Texture data is often the largest source of memory usage in a mobile application.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] In their seminal paper on texture compression, Beers, Agrawala and Chaddha list four features that tend to differentiate texture compression from other image compression techniques.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] It is highly desirable to be able to render directly from the compressed texture data and so, in order not to impact rendering performance, decompression must be fast.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] would be difficult, any texture compression scheme must allow fast random access to decompressed texture data.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] In a rendering system, lossy compression can be more tolerable than for other use cases.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Texture compression is more tolerant of asymmetric encoding/decoding rates as the encoding process is often done only once during the application authoring process.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Given the above, most texture compression algorithms involve some form of fixed-rate lossy vector quantization of small fixed-size blocks of pixels into small fixed-size blocks of coding bits, sometimes with additional extra pre-processing and post-processing steps.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Block Truncation Coding is a very simple example of this family of algorithms.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Because their data access patterns are well-defined, texture decompression may be executed on-the-fly during rendering as part of the overall graphics pipeline, reducing overall bandwidth and storage needs throughout the graphics system.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] As well as texture maps, texture compression may also be used to encode other kinds of rendering map, including bump maps and surface normal maps.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Texture compression may also be used together with other forms of map processing such as mipmaps and anisotropic filtering.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Some examples of practical texture compression systems are S3 Texture Compression (S3TC), PVRTC, Ericsson Texture Compression (ETC) and Adaptive Scalable Texture Compression (ASTC); these may be supported by special function units in modern graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] OpenGL and OpenGL ES, as implemented on many video accelerator cards and mobile GPUs, can support multiple common kinds of texture compression - generally through the use of vendor extensions.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] A compressed-texture can be further compressed in what is called "supercompression".
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Fixed-rate texture compression formats are optimized for random access and are much less efficient compared to image formats such as PNG.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] By adding further compression, a programmer can reduce the efficiency gap.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] The extra layer can be decompressed by the CPU so that the GPU receives a normal compressed texture, or in newer methods, decompressed by the GPU itself.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Supercompression saves the same amount of VRAM as regular texture compression, but saves more disk space and download size.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] Random-Access Neural Compression of Material Textures (Neural Texture Compression) is a Nvidia's technology which enables two additional levels of detail (16× more texels, so four times higher resolution) while maintaining similar storage requirements as traditional texture compression methods.
[src:texture-compression/texture-compression] The key idea is compressing multiple material textures and their mipmap chains together, and using a small neural network, that is optimized for each material, to decompress them.
